				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The most immediate concern would appear to be around the implications of the expansion of EU export refund operations, which could serve to exacerbate the consequences of the global dairy crisis for African producers, given the dominant role which the EU plays in the dairy trade into Africa. In the longer term, the increased role the EC is looking to take in monitoring the function of supply chains to ensure that no anti-competitive practices emerge could well be relevant to ACP suppliers, if such measures were extended to supply chains in which ACP suppliers play major roles (e.g. the sugar and horticultural product supply chains).</p><p>In terms of the internal regional implications within the EU of quota abolition, this has little impact on ACP countries, since the ACP have only very limited exports of dairy products to the EU. Of more potential interest is methodology for assessing the regional impact of abolition of quotas on the geographical distribution of production and the distribution of income along supply chains. These are both critical issues in the ACP sugar sector at the present time.</p>
		</div>
		
